00:13:50,096 --> 00:13:52,497
they all become very, very spiritual and religious.

257
00:13:52,697 --> 00:13:53,998
I mean, that's kind of like a joke

258
00:13:54,018 --> 00:13:55,619
I heard from a lunch table, right?

259
00:13:57,221 --> 00:13:59,482
And they say there must be something mysterious

260
00:13:59,522 --> 00:14:01,904
about the moon that really transformed

261
00:14:01,944 --> 00:14:02,925
these people who went there.

262
00:14:05,427 --> 00:14:12,190
And later on I met the guy who drove the first moon buggy and I asked him,

263
00:14:12,290 --> 00:14:17,112
so what is so special about the moon that makes these people feel different after they come back?

264
00:14:17,552 --> 00:14:20,073
And he said, you know, on the moon there's nothing.

265
00:14:20,874 --> 00:14:24,155
There's no sound because there's no air. It's utterly quiet.

266
00:14:24,775 --> 00:14:29,218
And the Earth is so small, it's like your thumbnail, you can just cover it up, you know.

267
00:14:30,859 --> 00:14:36,763
And you're on this strange place where there's nothing and there's no sound and you just can't stop but thinking

268
00:14:37,644 --> 00:14:37,964
Why?

269
00:14:39,065 --> 00:14:45,891
You know, why are we here? You know, what about the rest of the universe, you know, because everything you know, these these these

270
00:14:46,231 --> 00:14:51,135
Astronauts, they're mostly scientists. They know a lot about Earth's but and all of a sudden

271
00:14:52,034 --> 00:14:53,795
they're facing with a lot of unknown.

272
00:14:55,137 --> 00:14:59,561
And I learned psychology, I know that the sense of awe

273
00:14:59,801 --> 00:15:06,228
and unknown is directly tied to a lot of religious meanings.

274
00:15:07,029 --> 00:15:09,331
And so it's kind of an inspiration.

275
00:15:09,351 --> 00:15:11,473
It might not directly connect to what the game is,

276
00:15:11,513 --> 00:15:14,576
but it kind of inspired me looking at our life today.

277
00:15:16,246 --> 00:15:18,727
We are kind of super empowered by technology today.

278
00:15:19,627 --> 00:15:21,228
We can move really, really fast.

279
00:15:22,049 --> 00:15:24,990
We can live and work above the clouds.

280
00:15:26,050 --> 00:15:28,571
We can talk to anybody, talk to anybody

281
00:15:28,932 --> 00:15:30,532
at anywhere, at any time.

282
00:15:32,616 --> 00:15:38,980
and in our pocket or our bag, we carry the entire knowledge that human has ever gathered.

283
00:15:40,341 --> 00:15:45,045
It makes me feel powerful because if I get to bring the gadgets today to 10 years ago,

284
00:15:45,685 --> 00:15:51,549
they will think I'm a god. I know everything, I can do anything. But it also kind of makes me feel

285
00:15:51,569 --> 00:15:57,474
like we are living a life where we're trapped by these empowerment. We can't simply live without

286
00:15:57,514 --> 00:15:58,074
them anymore.

287
00:15:59,825 --> 00:16:01,025
And when you look at video games,

288
00:16:01,265 --> 00:16:03,887
and particularly the popular commercial games,

289
00:16:04,427 --> 00:16:07,329
you know, most of these characters are kind of,

290
00:16:07,649 --> 00:16:10,111
you know, carrying something, symbolize power.

291
00:16:10,251 --> 00:16:12,933
And the gameplay, you know, I mentioned earlier,

292
00:16:13,013 --> 00:16:14,274
is mostly about empowerment.

293
00:16:15,474 --> 00:16:16,695
And when you have empowerment,

294
00:16:17,569 --> 00:16:20,092
when you put a bunch of people in that environment,

295
00:16:20,273 --> 00:16:21,394
their first reaction is,

296
00:16:21,735 --> 00:16:25,159
how am I gonna apply my power on someone else, right?

297
00:16:25,500 --> 00:16:26,581
If you give me a gun,

298
00:16:27,302 --> 00:16:29,506
and you lock me up with another guy in a room,

299
00:16:29,526 --> 00:16:32,129
I think I'm gonna use it someday.

300
00:16:34,224 --> 00:16:39,407
So, the problem is, you know, when you have a lot of power,

301
00:16:39,907 --> 00:16:43,169
even though the game is supposed to be about survival

302
00:16:43,590 --> 00:16:45,691
and bonding and collaboration,

303
00:16:46,932 --> 00:16:48,613
most of the time you're applying your power,

304
00:16:48,633 --> 00:16:50,274
like let's say I'm shooting Left 4 Dead,

305
00:16:50,814 --> 00:16:53,195
and if my teammates block me, I'm like, ugh.

306
00:16:54,252 --> 00:16:56,693
Get away, you know, I'm gonna shoot this zombie.

307
00:16:57,634 --> 00:16:59,754
And the only time I felt a connection

308
00:16:59,854 --> 00:17:03,156
while playing Left 4 Dead is when someone was

309
00:17:03,616 --> 00:17:05,777
patching me up, and I really feel something,

310
00:17:05,817 --> 00:17:07,517
but too bad it's so rare.

311
00:17:08,237 --> 00:17:09,918
Most of the time, majority of the time,

312
00:17:09,958 --> 00:17:11,299
I'm still applying power.

313
00:17:13,559 --> 00:17:16,060
So when I think about redesigning a social experience,

314
00:17:16,120 --> 00:17:17,901
that's something that will connect people together,

315
00:17:19,791 --> 00:17:26,316
I think the very first important thing is to reverse the power relationship between

316
00:17:26,336 --> 00:17:27,777
the players and the world.

317
00:17:28,477 --> 00:17:33,260
The player needs to be less powerful and the monster needs to be more powerful.

318
00:17:33,701 --> 00:17:36,263
And then you will think about collaborating with other people.

319
00:17:36,883 --> 00:17:43,588
And in a lot of games today, it's mostly about achievements, you know, and challenge about

320
00:17:43,908 --> 00:17:44,788
conquering the monster.

321
00:17:44,828 --> 00:17:47,911
And too bad the monster logo looks like the Android logo.

322
00:17:48,691 --> 00:17:50,732
It has no indication here.

323
00:17:52,673 --> 00:17:56,074
So what I'm trying to see is that in an online game,

324
00:17:56,775 --> 00:17:58,836
you know, most people think about getting items

325
00:17:59,136 --> 00:18:02,457
and getting power and think less about the other player.

326
00:18:02,577 --> 00:18:04,358
And particularly in World of Warcraft,

327
00:18:05,299 --> 00:18:07,140
most of the time I don't think about the player,

328
00:18:07,240 --> 00:18:09,601
only when I'm like, this guy is too difficult to beat.

329
00:18:09,821 --> 00:18:12,302
I need another guy to help me to beat this boss.

330
00:18:13,162 --> 00:18:16,984
And I kind of think of them as a tool to get the treasure afterwards.

331
00:18:17,384 --> 00:18:18,605
And I want to see a reverse.

332
00:18:18,725 --> 00:18:24,448
I want to see the treasure and the monsters only being a means to make me realize how

333
00:18:24,588 --> 00:18:25,729
awesome the other players are.

334
00:18:27,955 --> 00:18:31,857
In most of the online games, it's about shooting,

335
00:18:32,277 --> 00:18:35,919
but I wanted to see online game where the skills

336
00:18:35,959 --> 00:18:37,840
the player gain and improve over time

337
00:18:37,920 --> 00:18:40,641
is actually about communicating emotions

338
00:18:41,582 --> 00:18:43,823
and really feel each other rather than just,

339
00:18:43,983 --> 00:18:45,964
you know, like how accurate your gunshot is.

340
00:18:48,962 --> 00:18:51,923
So, the problem, you know, trying to create that word

341
00:18:52,243 --> 00:18:55,144
is very difficult because in a lot of modern day games,

342
00:18:55,224 --> 00:18:57,284
the theme of war is just too noisy.

343
00:18:57,304 --> 00:19:00,525
You just don't have time to look at the other friend

344
00:19:00,625 --> 00:19:03,546
when a tank and a helicopter is attacking you.

345
00:19:03,586 --> 00:19:05,207
So I thought, well, it's easy.

346
00:19:05,247 --> 00:19:07,047
The first thing is we should get rid of the noise,

347
00:19:07,207 --> 00:19:10,368
and we just keep a game to focus on people.

348
00:19:11,529 --> 00:19:13,389
And then we have that problem where, you know,

349
00:19:13,469 --> 00:19:14,930
if I have a gun, I'm gonna use it,

350
00:19:15,090 --> 00:19:16,090
so we have to ditch that.

351
00:19:18,273 --> 00:19:24,175
And then, you know, it started to get interesting, you know, a bunch of people in a lobby kind of like waiting before the raid starts.

352
00:19:24,255 --> 00:19:25,556
They start to talk to each other.

353
00:19:26,916 --> 00:19:29,277
But I kind of wanted to have more structure.

354
00:19:29,837 --> 00:19:31,757
So I thought, well, what if we have less people?

355
00:19:31,777 --> 00:19:34,158
You know, it's easier to design when you have less people.

356
00:19:35,178 --> 00:19:37,859
Let's say we are in a very hazardous environment.

357
00:19:38,059 --> 00:19:39,460
Not many people can survive.

358
00:19:39,920 --> 00:19:41,140
And there's only two people left.

359
00:19:41,940 --> 00:19:43,921
And then, you know, all of a sudden,

360
00:19:43,941 --> 00:19:46,582
this guy in the distance become very, very interesting

361
00:19:47,503 --> 00:19:51,044
compared to, you know, a constant warfare of action.

362
00:19:52,925 --> 00:19:54,966
So that's kind of the very beginning of Journey.

363
00:19:55,526 --> 00:19:58,307
We wanted to have a game which make you feel

364
00:19:59,188 --> 00:20:01,809
somewhat lonely, somewhat small,

365
00:20:02,329 --> 00:20:04,590
but you have a great sense of awe

366
00:20:04,970 --> 00:20:07,531
and the feeling of unknown towards

367
00:20:09,312 --> 00:20:10,953
the mystery behind this game world.

368
00:20:12,968 --> 00:20:16,010
But that's just a kind of emotion we identified,

369
00:20:16,050 --> 00:20:18,271
but to actually execute that emotion,

370
00:20:18,652 --> 00:20:19,992
we have to do a lot of prototyping,

371
00:20:20,032 --> 00:20:22,074
because we have not seen a lot of games

372
00:20:22,134 --> 00:20:23,775
that's trying to achieve that.

373
00:20:23,795 --> 00:20:26,917
Maybe Myst or Shadow of the Colossus is the only two

374
00:20:26,997 --> 00:20:29,859
I can see that is actually having similar feeling.

375
00:20:31,280 --> 00:20:32,901
So when we prototype,

376
00:20:32,921 --> 00:20:35,262
I actually always start prototyping music.

377
00:20:36,583 --> 00:20:41,049
it's not the interactivity because music is the most effective and powerful medium

378
00:20:41,330 --> 00:20:47,719
that can create emotion. So I work with Austin Wintory, by the way he's Grammy nominated.

379
00:20:53,771 --> 00:21:00,777
I was really really lucky to have a music that he made pretty much like right beginning of the

380
00:21:00,917 --> 00:21:08,804
development. So four months into Journey's development, our artist made this mock-up

381
00:21:08,884 --> 00:21:12,167
trailer with Austin's music and I'm just going to play it here.

382
00:21:27,992 --> 00:21:31,875
And you can see in the early days, our character looks like a ninja.

383
00:21:36,278 --> 00:21:44,244
And he still has like a human shape, he has arms, you know, it's very much the early stage.

384
00:21:44,424 --> 00:21:51,749
But we know the world needs to make you feel big and inspiring, and you need to feel small.

385
00:21:54,257 --> 00:21:59,299
So, it's kind of various landscape, but you can hear the music, that's the music we used

386
00:21:59,399 --> 00:22:00,240
in the endgame.

387
00:22:00,820 --> 00:22:05,222
It's the music you would hear on a cross-media buy before you launch the journey.

388
00:22:05,742 --> 00:22:10,704
It has not changed, it just hits something strong and I really feel there's something

389
00:22:10,744 --> 00:22:10,944
there.

390
00:22:12,184 --> 00:22:14,645
And we kind of start to build the game around this music.

391
00:22:18,407 --> 00:22:20,228
And the mountain used to be a...

392
00:22:20,982 --> 00:22:23,646
crevice of a canyon rather than a hill.

393
00:22:23,826 --> 00:22:30,094
All right.

394
00:22:30,675 --> 00:22:31,075
And so...

395
00:22:31,095 --> 00:22:31,135
So...

396
00:22:35,107 --> 00:22:37,970
Then we start to enter all kinds of RAM problems.

397
00:22:38,070 --> 00:22:40,754
You know, like, I think the trailer is the only thing successful in the early day.

398
00:22:42,196 --> 00:22:44,919
So, okay, let me show you something we learned, right?

399
00:22:45,119 --> 00:22:47,923
We started prototyping with co-op

400
00:22:48,063 --> 00:22:50,166
because we know we wanted people to work with each other.

401
00:22:50,666 --> 00:22:52,729
So we started this prototype called Rope.

402
00:22:53,810 --> 00:22:56,591
So basically it's a one button game, you just press space.

403
00:22:57,972 --> 00:23:00,333
And rope is the action, you know, in the chat bubble

404
00:23:00,353 --> 00:23:03,034
it's the action, and you can see a long legged guy

405
00:23:03,474 --> 00:23:05,555
can't break rock because he doesn't have arm.

406
00:23:05,975 --> 00:23:08,717
But the fat guy, he has strength, so he can break a rock.

407
00:23:09,217 --> 00:23:11,858
But still the chance is not always 100%, right?

408
00:23:12,398 --> 00:23:15,279
And so as they collaborate, here's a rope

409
00:23:15,320 --> 00:23:16,020
so they can climb up.

410
00:23:18,219 --> 00:23:21,261
So the long-legged guy runs fast and he can jump through gaps.

411
00:23:21,941 --> 00:23:24,002
And so, well, he didn't do it that time.

412
00:23:24,643 --> 00:23:28,785
But with a rope, because anybody can lower a rope at any time,

413
00:23:29,846 --> 00:23:34,088
eventually, with the chance, they can collaborate.

414
00:23:34,931 --> 00:23:37,432
And we thought this is a great game, you know, you help each other,

415
00:23:37,893 --> 00:23:41,115
but then, you know, the problem is like, what if you're playing alone?

416
00:23:41,276 --> 00:23:42,256
You can't play this game.

417
00:23:42,577 --> 00:23:48,802
And, you know, Sony keep telling us that this game could have a great multiplayer,

418
00:23:48,842 --> 00:23:50,383
but it needs to have a single player.

419
00:23:50,763 --> 00:23:53,105
Otherwise, you will not sell your game, right?

420
00:23:53,185 --> 00:23:55,087
And so we're like, okay, well, this doesn't work.

421
00:23:56,087 --> 00:23:57,268
And here's an example where...

422
00:23:58,616 --> 00:24:01,458
Two people are collaborating and they're pushing a heavy rock.

423
00:24:01,698 --> 00:24:06,120
I mean, this is a very common co-op feature I think most co-op games have.

424
00:24:06,760 --> 00:24:09,101
But if you're alone, you can't even finish this level.

425
00:24:10,342 --> 00:24:15,424
Even though there's a great feeling of collaboration, it becomes quite a trouble for us when we

426
00:24:15,484 --> 00:24:18,766
wanted to design a game where it's possible to play alone.

427
00:24:20,970 --> 00:24:22,971
And the other thing, you know, as you can see,

428
00:24:23,011 --> 00:24:25,973
most of the prototype early on is like Java and Flash.

429
00:24:26,033 --> 00:24:27,895
They're 2D prototypes.

430
00:24:27,915 --> 00:24:29,996
And stuff we thought was brilliant.

431
00:24:31,363 --> 00:24:32,784
didn't walk in 3D at all.

432
00:24:33,165 --> 00:24:36,389
So we started this idea about trail.

433
00:24:36,509 --> 00:24:37,930
So if you walk in a desert,

434
00:24:38,050 --> 00:24:40,193
you can only see so far and from the top down,

435
00:24:40,633 --> 00:24:42,095
how would you know there's other player?

436
00:24:42,555 --> 00:24:44,197
And even if the other player exists,

437
00:24:44,478 --> 00:24:46,260
if they're moving towards one direction,

438
00:24:46,600 --> 00:24:47,861
how are you ever gonna catch up

439
00:24:48,062 --> 00:24:49,403
if you all have the same speed?

440
00:24:49,884 --> 00:24:51,786
So if you walk on other people's trail,

441
00:24:52,126 --> 00:24:52,767
you will speed up.

442
00:24:54,825 --> 00:24:57,225
And so eventually, you know, as you explore,

443
00:24:57,265 --> 00:24:58,426
you will run into other player,

444
00:24:58,486 --> 00:25:01,906
and you can see the shout has been, you know,

445
00:25:02,907 --> 00:25:04,847
very early prototype, I think that was a success.

446
00:25:05,207 --> 00:25:06,487
But in here, I'm trying to show you

447
00:25:06,527 --> 00:25:09,648
that if the player can be next to each other,

448
00:25:09,888 --> 00:25:12,369
they become more strengthful, and they can climb up rocks.

449
00:25:14,209 --> 00:25:16,629
And, you know, but these mechanics,

450
00:25:17,450 --> 00:25:19,450
eventually when you transfer into 3D,

451
00:25:19,770 --> 00:25:22,391
it's almost impossible to actually pull it off

452
00:25:22,411 --> 00:25:23,311
because cameras.

453
00:25:24,192 --> 00:25:24,812
and other things.

454
00:25:25,213 --> 00:25:28,096
So here's another prototype we thought was smart

455
00:25:28,136 --> 00:25:29,498
is when the two people are traveling,

456
00:25:29,518 --> 00:25:30,759
they get to go faster

457
00:25:30,779 --> 00:25:32,901
because they can leapfrog from each other

458
00:25:33,542 --> 00:25:36,445
and they can increase the speed.

459
00:25:38,339 --> 00:25:40,600
Another great idea we had, we thought it was smart,

460
00:25:40,700 --> 00:25:44,523
is the idea of calling to distracting the monster.

461
00:25:44,984 --> 00:25:46,725
In Journey, you see the monster, right?

462
00:25:46,745 --> 00:25:47,766
But if you shout at them,

463
00:25:47,786 --> 00:25:49,927
then the monster will not attack you.

464
00:25:50,008 --> 00:25:51,309
So between the two players,

465
00:25:51,669 --> 00:25:54,291
you might be able to collaborate and distract the monster

466
00:25:54,711 --> 00:25:55,432
and to get through.

467
00:25:56,853 --> 00:25:59,974
But when we actually try to execute this idea in 3D,

468
00:26:00,655 --> 00:26:02,876
it's almost impossible to tell the distance

469
00:26:02,996 --> 00:26:05,297
between you and the monster and coordinate.

470
00:26:05,697 --> 00:26:07,658
It's just way too hard.

471
00:26:08,639 --> 00:26:12,241
And it tells me that a top-down view is great

472
00:26:12,261 --> 00:26:14,622
for strategical maneuver and collaboration,

473
00:26:14,662 --> 00:26:16,183
but it's almost impossible in 3D.

474
00:26:18,458 --> 00:26:21,860
So here's another scenario which we really saw

475
00:26:21,900 --> 00:26:23,521
was a great idea which also got killed.

476
00:26:24,502 --> 00:26:25,683
You know, we thought about desert,

477
00:26:25,783 --> 00:26:27,043
of course there's sandstorm.

478
00:26:27,504 --> 00:26:30,746
So sandstorm is coming and people need to find a shelter.

479
00:26:31,426 --> 00:26:33,067
The shelter is kind of a gray color.

480
00:26:33,868 --> 00:26:35,789
And you can see the sandstorm keep going.

481
00:26:36,490 --> 00:26:38,591
If they stay in the shelter too intimately,

482
00:26:38,631 --> 00:26:40,132
the color of them will change to pink.

483
00:26:41,213 --> 00:26:42,914
I don't know what that means, maybe they're shy.

484
00:26:44,815 --> 00:26:45,235
And so,

485
00:26:46,848 --> 00:26:50,430
this very scene of the sandstorm wiping the entire world

486
00:26:52,371 --> 00:26:53,851
was a very powerful emotional experience,

487
00:26:53,871 --> 00:26:55,752
but in the end, when we bring it to 3D,

488
00:26:56,213 --> 00:26:59,955
we realize how difficult it is to actually do a sandstorm,

489
00:27:00,455 --> 00:27:01,315
and we just couldn't do it.

490
00:27:03,036 --> 00:27:06,738
And there's also this idea about graphics as gameplay.

491
00:27:07,218 --> 00:27:09,379
This is something very unique in TGC.

492
00:27:10,020 --> 00:27:11,781
Internally, we call it a gameplay,

493
00:27:14,513 --> 00:27:19,596
We are more of a gameplay company than than gameplay mechanics company. What do I mean? So

494
00:27:20,596 --> 00:27:25,839
Imagine you're in the desert and you're walking towards a mountain in the distance and you've been walking

495
00:27:26,771 --> 00:27:30,833
And the mountain is so far, there's almost nothing changing on screen.

496
00:27:31,133 --> 00:27:36,315
And this is kind of how it feels early on in the journey, where we have to keep dropping

497
00:27:36,375 --> 00:27:41,557
breadcrumbs to keep the player feel like, oh, am I actually making some progress?

498
00:27:42,297 --> 00:27:46,238
The world is so big, you know, we want it to feel epic, but then it's really boring

499
00:27:46,258 --> 00:27:47,499
to traverse through the land.

500
00:27:48,339 --> 00:27:51,320
And for quite a long time, we were like, this game is not fun at all.

501
00:27:53,217 --> 00:27:57,601
So in order to create feedback for simple traversal,

502
00:27:57,621 --> 00:28:00,703
like walking, we added the sand trail

503
00:28:00,923 --> 00:28:02,425
so at least you're enjoying something.

504
00:28:02,465 --> 00:28:04,446
You can sense how long you've been walked.

505
00:28:05,407 --> 00:28:08,770
And we wanted to have a lot more dunes and things

506
00:28:08,810 --> 00:28:11,172
that would be passing by so when you walk,

507
00:28:11,612 --> 00:28:13,674
the entire screen is giving you feedback

508
00:28:13,714 --> 00:28:15,255
rather than just staring at an image.

509
00:28:16,416 --> 00:28:19,818
So we went out to a real kind of desert beach.

510
00:28:20,199 --> 00:28:21,220
This is the Pismo Beach.

511
00:28:23,112 --> 00:28:26,454
And here's a video of our lead engineer, John Edwards,

512
00:28:26,554 --> 00:28:27,374
climbing the sand.

513
00:28:28,255 --> 00:28:30,316
And I'm like, if you jump off the sand,

514
00:28:30,416 --> 00:28:33,497
can you actually slide down, you know, like sand slide?

515
00:28:33,577 --> 00:28:37,599
And so here I'm telling him, hey, you know, let's try this.

516
00:28:37,659 --> 00:28:39,820
Let's try, just jump off, see what's gonna happen.

517
00:28:41,461 --> 00:28:42,601
So here he jumps down,

518
00:28:45,002 --> 00:28:45,983
and then just stopped.

519
00:28:47,096 --> 00:28:48,757
Right? And how terrible is that?

520
00:28:49,778 --> 00:28:55,062
And so, I wish in the ideal world he would just be sliding down, right?

521
00:28:55,162 --> 00:28:58,724
And that's what we did exactly in Journey, which is like,

522
00:28:59,445 --> 00:29:04,549
you climb up kind of slowly, and then eventually you kind of like slide down on the other side.

523
00:29:06,470 --> 00:29:09,993
You know, it's kind of weird, it's like we're trying to capture realism,

524
00:29:10,073 --> 00:29:13,095
but we're trying to capture the realism that we wished.

525
00:29:14,874 --> 00:29:19,956
So, you know, then walking becomes interesting because every dune you climb up, you have

526
00:29:20,016 --> 00:29:24,057
this anticipation of what's behind it, and you also have a reward.

527
00:29:24,177 --> 00:29:27,699
So there's a lot more engagement in the basic movement.

528
00:29:27,819 --> 00:29:31,340
And there's no mechanics here, really, just the feedback.

529
00:29:33,192 --> 00:29:36,074
So as we work on this game, we run into a lot of distractions.

530
00:29:36,674 --> 00:29:39,275
As a good designer, you need to be very clear

531
00:29:39,295 --> 00:29:43,517
about the experience you want and stay the hell away

532
00:29:43,597 --> 00:29:45,418
from the experience you don't want.

533
00:29:47,479 --> 00:29:49,499
So Journey is a very simple.

534
00:29:51,072 --> 00:29:54,053
Interface game because we wanted to make it for everybody, you know

535
00:29:54,093 --> 00:29:56,314
We want a kid to be able to pick up the game to play

536
00:29:56,814 --> 00:30:02,656
We want to give this to my dad or my mom and they should be able to just enjoy it rather than learning a lot

537
00:30:02,696 --> 00:30:03,536
about gaming

538
00:30:05,077 --> 00:30:09,778
So when I think about online game, the first thing I think about is the online interface, you know

539
00:30:09,798 --> 00:30:13,839
This is Journey's online interface. There's another guy. So, you know, it's online game, right?

540
00:30:15,320 --> 00:30:17,722
And then when I think about online games,

541
00:30:18,123 --> 00:30:20,825
before we made this game, it was like this, right?

542
00:30:21,005 --> 00:30:24,788
You have to figure out a lobby, check out a room,

543
00:30:24,888 --> 00:30:26,569
and check everybody's pin number,

544
00:30:26,589 --> 00:30:29,252
and make sure it's all green, and then you start the game,

545
00:30:29,652 --> 00:30:31,633
and you have to say, you know, ready.

546
00:30:32,394 --> 00:30:34,696
And I just don't know how I'm gonna explain

547
00:30:34,716 --> 00:30:36,577
what is a pin number to my mom.

548
00:30:39,514 --> 00:30:41,776
So we say, well, we have to hide all these interfaces.

549
00:30:42,797 --> 00:30:46,821
And the next problem is just the user IDs, right?

550
00:30:46,901 --> 00:30:50,484
You know, like, because player has been playing

551
00:30:50,524 --> 00:30:52,066
the aggressive competitive games,

552
00:30:52,266 --> 00:30:54,248
and their name tend to be very aggressive.

553
00:30:54,348 --> 00:30:55,629
This name is actually not too bad.

554
00:30:58,790 --> 00:31:00,792
they actually take me out of the game.

555
00:31:01,112 --> 00:31:03,513
Even with Paris, well, Harris Hilton,

556
00:31:03,533 --> 00:31:06,475
but I'm seeing Paris Hilton, I'm seeing real world.

557
00:31:07,095 --> 00:31:10,157
It takes so much effort for us to transport

558
00:31:10,497 --> 00:31:13,879
the player from their living room into a magical realm.

559
00:31:14,579 --> 00:31:17,501
And these names, these texts just bring them back.

560
00:31:18,181 --> 00:31:21,143
And I really think in order to have them collaborate

561
00:31:21,243 --> 00:31:25,905
and connect, they have to forget these real life things.

562
00:31:27,306 --> 00:31:29,228
And the next thing is people will say,

563
00:31:29,348 --> 00:31:31,730
oh, online game, I get to talk to my friends, right?

564
00:31:31,750 --> 00:31:33,772
I need to have voice chat, or at least I can type.

565
00:31:36,154 --> 00:31:38,797
And knowing console games,

566
00:31:39,577 --> 00:31:41,799
I just really don't want to hear the voice

567
00:31:41,880 --> 00:31:43,441
of the 12-years-old boy.

568
00:31:45,223 --> 00:31:48,466
And who knows who's playing the games on the other side, right?

569
00:31:49,066 --> 00:31:49,146
And...

570
00:31:50,915 --> 00:31:52,917
But Sony was talking to us that, you know,

571
00:31:53,277 --> 00:31:55,418
if you have friends invite, you know,

572
00:31:55,498 --> 00:31:58,320
you can have a viral marketing, right?

573
00:31:59,140 --> 00:32:00,641
Because it's fun to play with friends,

574
00:32:00,681 --> 00:32:02,142
they will tell other player to buy the game.

575
00:32:02,723 --> 00:32:04,364
And we thought this is good idea,

576
00:32:04,904 --> 00:32:06,165
but when you implement that,

577
00:32:06,485 --> 00:32:08,486
if you have two stranger on the internet,

578
00:32:08,846 --> 00:32:10,727
and they can't chat, they can accept that.

579
00:32:11,388 --> 00:32:13,629
But if I'm playing with my best friend,

580
00:32:14,249 --> 00:32:16,110
and he's on the internet, and we can't chat,

581
00:32:16,190 --> 00:32:17,190
it's kind of frustrating.

582
00:32:17,811 --> 00:32:19,932
And because of that, we actually decided

583
00:32:19,952 --> 00:32:21,672
to not even support friends invites,

584
00:32:22,052 --> 00:32:24,654
because it would break the integrity of the word.

585
00:32:26,734 --> 00:32:31,136
So the only way we allow players to connect

586
00:32:31,156 --> 00:32:33,737
with each other is at the very end of the game,

587
00:32:34,178 --> 00:32:36,118
after all the critics rose up,

588
00:32:36,659 --> 00:32:39,120
the very end, we show you the ID of the other player.

589
00:32:41,726 --> 00:32:46,389
And so that way we can protect the feeling between the strangers.

590
00:32:47,930 --> 00:32:52,512
And the other distraction is in the early days when we tried 4-player co-op,

591
00:32:53,393 --> 00:32:55,934
we realized there are a lot of weird situations, like

592
00:32:56,855 --> 00:33:00,657
after they play for a while, they start to talk about us versus them.

593
00:33:01,557 --> 00:33:03,079
They suck, you know, we are great.

594
00:33:03,859 --> 00:33:06,021
And I'm thinking, well, sure,

595
00:33:06,502 --> 00:33:08,263
having competition is great for online games,

596
00:33:08,303 --> 00:33:12,107
but that's not the emotional connection I'm thinking about.

597
00:33:13,408 --> 00:33:16,991
And the worst case is when there are three players,

598
00:33:17,031 --> 00:33:17,892
they're a bigger group.

599
00:33:18,773 --> 00:33:20,735
And this single player is isolated.

600
00:33:20,755 --> 00:33:23,879
I remember talking to my professor, Tracy Fullerton,

601
00:33:23,899 --> 00:33:26,583
who's sitting here, and she told me she hated this game

602
00:33:27,043 --> 00:33:29,787
because she's an explorer, she wants to explore the game,

603
00:33:29,827 --> 00:33:32,270
but all the other testers wanted to move on.

604
00:33:32,890 --> 00:33:36,174
And she felt forced, she has to conform herself

605
00:33:36,815 --> 00:33:37,416
towards others.

606
00:33:38,780 --> 00:33:40,482
And so in the end we start to focus on

607
00:33:41,043 --> 00:33:42,164
one-on-one interaction.

608
00:33:42,585 --> 00:33:45,908
But also based on that particular problem

609
00:33:45,948 --> 00:33:47,410
with the three versus one,

610
00:33:47,490 --> 00:33:50,313
I wanna bring this idea of collaboration and flow.

611
00:33:52,300 --> 00:33:56,004
So, Flow, originally, I learned it through making

612
00:33:57,425 --> 00:33:58,906
the single-player game, because, you know,

613
00:33:59,727 --> 00:34:02,830
as a psychology theory, Flow is about the balance

614
00:34:02,910 --> 00:34:05,832
between the player's ability and the challenge of the game.

615
00:34:06,173 --> 00:34:08,795
And you want to make sure, no matter where the player

616
00:34:09,956 --> 00:34:12,558
evolves in the game, they're in this nice balance.

617
00:34:13,159 --> 00:34:16,522
But also, there's this concept of the flow for collaboration.

618
00:34:17,603 --> 00:34:21,145
or in Bernie DeKoven's word, collaboration,

619
00:34:21,266 --> 00:34:23,487
which is like in any group co-op,

620
00:34:24,748 --> 00:34:26,770
there's a balance between the individualism

621
00:34:27,510 --> 00:34:28,972
and the group conformity.

622
00:34:28,992 --> 00:34:30,833
You can't just be too much about yourself,

623
00:34:30,893 --> 00:34:32,274
then the group will abandon you.

624
00:34:32,815 --> 00:34:35,317
And you can't just always do what the group wants you to do,

625
00:34:35,397 --> 00:34:36,417
then you lose yourself.

626
00:34:37,538 --> 00:34:39,580
And the player needs to have the choice

627
00:34:40,100 --> 00:34:42,342
to actually navigate through the experience,

628
00:34:42,682 --> 00:34:43,683
to stay in the flow,

629
00:34:43,983 --> 00:34:46,065
and also to stay in the flow of collaboration.

630
00:34:47,006 --> 00:34:53,110
And that's really why we try really hard to create Journey's seamless online lobby system,

631
00:34:53,190 --> 00:34:56,352
where, you know, we will match you up with all kinds of players,

632
00:34:56,753 --> 00:34:58,954
but some of them might not match with you.

633
00:35:00,035 --> 00:35:04,198
They might be explore, but you wanted to finish the game as quick as possible.

634
00:35:04,879 --> 00:35:08,162
But we believe if you have the choice to walk away from a player,

635
00:35:09,063 --> 00:35:12,707
eventually you will run into someone who wants to do the same thing,

636
00:35:12,767 --> 00:35:16,731
who is a similar type of player, and then you would love to be next to the player.

637
00:35:17,171 --> 00:35:22,056
When they have the choice to leave, the co-op is actually more real and sincere,

638
00:35:22,076 --> 00:35:25,860
and I think it's possible to have a stronger emotional connection.

639
00:35:27,286 --> 00:35:32,531
And so in the end, Journey's online matching system is based on the physical distance.

640
00:35:32,671 --> 00:35:35,494
You know, if someone's close to you, we will match you up.

641
00:35:35,894 --> 00:35:38,637
But if you don't like them, you start to kind of walk away.

642
00:35:39,718 --> 00:35:42,400
The system will disconnect them and find someone else.

643
00:35:44,624 --> 00:35:47,025
Another type of distraction, resource, right?

644
00:35:48,005 --> 00:35:51,147
In Journey, you go through, pick up those cloth strands,

645
00:35:52,767 --> 00:35:54,688
and you fly, and you love them.

646
00:35:56,429 --> 00:35:59,370
And when two people who love strands, they meet,

647
00:35:59,891 --> 00:36:02,012
and one guy take the resource, and he fly,

648
00:36:02,552 --> 00:36:03,813
then the other guys hate you.

649
00:36:05,153 --> 00:36:08,335
And in fact, in our early days of playtesting,

650
00:36:08,395 --> 00:36:09,155
people were saying like,

651
00:36:09,775 --> 00:36:11,616
I really don't want to be with the other player.

652
00:36:12,557 --> 00:36:15,141
They don't belong here because they're going to steal my resource.

653
00:36:16,696 --> 00:36:19,438
So for quite a while, in order to compensate,

654
00:36:19,538 --> 00:36:20,800
we thought we have a great idea.

655
00:36:20,840 --> 00:36:23,102
We have the player who drops the resource

656
00:36:23,182 --> 00:36:24,002
after they use them,

657
00:36:24,022 --> 00:36:26,284
so they don't actually consume resource.

658
00:36:26,945 --> 00:36:29,107
So maybe that way the player will love them.

659
00:36:29,167 --> 00:36:32,250
So this is an early stage kind of 3D prototype.

660
00:36:32,810 --> 00:36:34,492
And you can see if the player flies,

661
00:36:34,552 --> 00:36:37,754
he drops all these kind of strands right behind them.

662
00:36:38,315 --> 00:36:39,996
So for the other player,

663
00:36:40,036 --> 00:36:42,178
he can just pick them up and fly up for free.

664
00:36:43,350 --> 00:36:46,474
It's kind of like a communism thing, you know, you share all the resources.

665
00:36:48,405 --> 00:36:52,427
But the problem is that even though mathematically you share it,

666
00:36:53,287 --> 00:36:54,528
psychologically you don't.

667
00:36:55,608 --> 00:36:58,610
A lot of players complain about how I picked up all these resources

668
00:36:58,670 --> 00:37:00,871
and I carried all the way to the other guy

669
00:37:00,991 --> 00:37:02,872
and he got to use my resources to fly.

670
00:37:03,412 --> 00:37:04,993
He takes advantage of my labor,

671
00:37:05,473 --> 00:37:07,354
even though most of them are not intentional.

672
00:37:07,715 --> 00:37:10,796
And a lot of people feel kind of very weird

673
00:37:10,836 --> 00:37:12,657
where there's a guy stalking you

674
00:37:12,977 --> 00:37:14,778
and stay behind you and just pick up your stuff.

675
00:37:16,580 --> 00:37:21,509
And so they just think this is, you know, they still feel like there's some kind of stealing happening.

676
00:37:23,518 --> 00:37:26,059
So in order to really eliminate that,

677
00:37:26,299 --> 00:37:28,280
so at least people don't hate each other,

678
00:37:28,720 --> 00:37:32,261
we decided to drop the idea of possession, like resource.

679
00:37:33,062 --> 00:37:34,682
We just have infinite resource,

680
00:37:35,302 --> 00:37:38,163
except the player have limited pocket size.

681
00:37:38,203 --> 00:37:40,184
You can only carry this much money, right?

682
00:37:40,624 --> 00:37:43,105
So, and people go to resource,

683
00:37:43,145 --> 00:37:45,266
they all pick up their money, and they can all fly,

684
00:37:45,786 --> 00:37:46,966
and they don't hate each other.

685
00:37:48,507 --> 00:37:49,727
And then, at some point,

686
00:37:49,847 --> 00:37:51,928
we have another distraction from physics.

687
00:37:53,974 --> 00:37:55,755
In most online games, there's no collision,

688
00:37:55,795 --> 00:37:57,436
so people can't just walk through each other

689
00:37:57,857 --> 00:37:59,878
because collision online is very difficult to do

690
00:38:00,078 --> 00:38:01,760
and it causes all kinds of problem.

691
00:38:04,009 --> 00:38:06,250
And at some point, we talk about the two people

692
00:38:06,310 --> 00:38:07,771
helping each other to go through a rock.

693
00:38:07,871 --> 00:38:10,273
You can see in a 2D prototype, it's very easy,

694
00:38:10,833 --> 00:38:13,115
but to do this in 3D, you need to be able to

695
00:38:13,215 --> 00:38:14,896
carry the guy, push him up, and the other guy

696
00:38:14,936 --> 00:38:17,378
have to pull you up, so there's a lot of collision

697
00:38:17,398 --> 00:38:20,119
we have to, physics have to be implemented.

698
00:38:20,720 --> 00:38:22,941
So we thought, well, but this is gonna make people

699
00:38:23,021 --> 00:38:24,662
trust and help each other even more.

700
00:38:25,963 --> 00:38:28,425
Let's do this, this is gonna make this emotion deeper.

701
00:38:29,205 --> 00:38:34,630
So we added the physics so the player can actually push each other, you know, they feel the existence of each other.

702
00:38:34,650 --> 00:38:35,791
This is great.

703
00:38:37,013 --> 00:38:42,137
But instead of helping each other to push them onto the rock, they'd like to push them onto something more exotic.

704
00:38:44,336 --> 00:38:46,937
So, and for quite a while I thought it was just,

705
00:38:47,398 --> 00:38:48,458
you know, those playtests,

706
00:38:48,478 --> 00:38:49,679
they play too much Call of Duties,

707
00:38:49,719 --> 00:38:51,520
they're just mean, right?

708
00:38:52,220 --> 00:38:56,983
And then we were doing playtests at our own office.

709
00:38:57,183 --> 00:38:58,624
You know, our lead engineer, John Edwards,

710
00:38:58,644 --> 00:39:00,225
who was the guy who jumped off the sand,

711
00:39:00,845 --> 00:39:01,325
killed me.

712
00:39:03,226 --> 00:39:04,067
And multiple times.

713
00:39:04,507 --> 00:39:06,708
I'm like, wait, you know this game is about

714
00:39:06,788 --> 00:39:08,709
helping each other and having a connection, right?

715
00:39:09,250 --> 00:39:10,190
Why do you keep doing this?

716
00:39:11,170 --> 00:39:14,152
And he just stared at me laughing because we are just right across the office.

717
00:39:14,192 --> 00:39:15,393
I'm like, come on, revive me.

718
00:39:16,214 --> 00:39:16,414
Right.

719
00:39:17,655 --> 00:39:21,217
And then I realized for quite a while I was disappointed about humanity.

720
00:39:21,237 --> 00:39:24,259
So so.

721
00:39:27,893 --> 00:39:29,634
I was so disappointed and one day,

722
00:39:30,734 --> 00:39:34,615
Kylie told me to meet her brother's girlfriend.

723
00:39:34,695 --> 00:39:37,196
She is a spiritual psychologist.

724
00:39:38,777 --> 00:39:41,737
So I talked to her about this very, very dilemma

725
00:39:41,777 --> 00:39:42,738
about humanity, right?

726
00:39:43,638 --> 00:39:46,859
And she said, oh, you know, it's because your players,

727
00:39:47,499 --> 00:39:48,499
they're babies.

728
00:39:49,780 --> 00:39:50,820
What do I mean by that?

729
00:39:50,860 --> 00:39:52,560
You know, like when you transport yourself

730
00:39:52,660 --> 00:39:54,421
from the real world to a virtual space,

731
00:39:54,481 --> 00:39:56,501
particularly when character looks like dots.

732
00:39:57,688 --> 00:40:00,669
they don't carry the morality from our real life, right?

733
00:40:00,729 --> 00:40:01,889
It's like a new baby.

734
00:40:02,409 --> 00:40:03,870
And baby only seek for feedback.

735
00:40:04,510 --> 00:40:08,330
And pushing a guy to a rock has almost no feedback, right?

736
00:40:08,631 --> 00:40:10,391
But pushing a guy to kill them,

737
00:40:10,851 --> 00:40:12,371
there's animation, there's blood,

738
00:40:12,411 --> 00:40:14,412
there's a sound of crying,

739
00:40:14,532 --> 00:40:19,613
and there's social anxiety of waiting you to revive them.

740
00:40:19,753 --> 00:40:20,993
It's so much more rewarding.

741
00:40:21,693 --> 00:40:23,333
Of course, the player wants to do that.

742
00:40:24,273 --> 00:40:26,875
So what I learned is that the morality

743
00:40:26,915 --> 00:40:28,216
doesn't necessarily carry over,

744
00:40:28,376 --> 00:40:30,637
and in order to shape players' behavior,

745
00:40:31,218 --> 00:40:33,239
you have to control the input and output.

746
00:40:33,720 --> 00:40:35,501
So in order to prevent this happen,

747
00:40:35,741 --> 00:40:38,103
we actually get rid of collision in the end.

